                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72112/1872</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_PWH1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-07-22T18:00:00+00:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">July 22, 1915, 6 p. m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 7.34 p. m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2510. <persName corresp="#p_GSE1">Sir Edward Grey</persName> has just informed me
                    that he has telegraphed his Ambassador at Washington that the British Government
                    will make cotton contraband before the new crop gets to market. The British
                    commercial attaché at Washington is instructed to confer with the cotton
                    interests and to [come] to some satisfactory working arrangement whereby this
                    country will buy large quantities at a good price. Whatever arrangement is made
                    will be announced when the announcement is made that cotton will be
                    contraband.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">American Ambassador</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
